      <header class="pg-header">
        <p class="pg-eyebrow">Wednesday</p>
        <h1 class="pg-title">Woden</h1>
        <p class="pg-subtitle">Norse chief god — Odin, master of magic, runes, and the dead</p>
      </header>

      <p>
        Every Wednesday on the Gregorian calendar honors the chief god of the Norse pantheon. His Anglo-Saxon name was <strong>Woden</strong>; in Old Norse he was called <strong>Odin</strong>. He was the highest god of the Germanic peoples — the king of Asgard, the patron of poets and warriors, and the master of magic, runes, and the dead.
      </p>

      <h2>Who He Was</h2>

      <p>
        Odin (Woden) was the chief god of the Norse pantheon — husband of Frigg (whose name became Friday), father of Thor (whose name became Thursday), and ruler of Asgard. He was associated with everything the pagan world prized: kingship, war, poetry, prophecy, magic, and the gathering of slain warriors into Valhalla. He was also a god of the dead. His warriors believed that dying in battle was the greatest honor, because Odin himself would receive their souls.
      </p>

      <p>
        His most famous myth is the one in which he hangs himself on the world-tree Yggdrasil for nine days and nights, pierced by his own spear, in order to gain the secret of the runes — the magical alphabet of the gods. The picture of a god self-sacrificed on a tree to gain hidden knowledge is its own dark imitation of the truth, and it should not be missed: the pagan world's chief god was a sorcerer who taught his followers to cast runes and consult the dead.
      </p>

      <p>
        The Romans identified Woden with their god Mercury — both were associated with travel, communication, and the guidance of souls. The Roman day of Mercury (<em>dies Mercurii</em>) became the day of Woden in Germanic lands. Old English <em>Wōdnesdæg</em> became Wednesday. In Romance languages the day still bears Mercury's Latin name: French <em>mercredi</em>, Italian <em>mercoledì</em>, Spanish <em>miércoles</em>.
      </p>

      <h2>Why It Matters</h2>

      <p>
        Yahuah condemns rune-casting, divination, and consulting the dead in the strongest possible terms — and Woden was the patron of all three.
      </p>

      <div class="pg-scripture">
        <span class="ref">Deuteronomy 18:10–12</span> — "There shall not be found among you any one that… useth divination, or an observer of times, or an enchanter, or a witch, or a charmer, or a consulter with familiar spirits, or a wizard, or a necromancer. For all that do these things are an abomination unto Yahuah…"
      </div>

      <div class="pg-scripture">
        <span class="ref">Leviticus 19:31</span> — "Regard not them that have familiar spirits, neither seek after wizards, to be defiled by them: I am Yahuah your Elohim."
      </div>

      <p>
        Woden is, by his own mythology, exactly the kind of being Yahuah's people are forbidden to consult. He is a wizard. He is a master of runes — a divination system. He is a god of the dead who receives souls. To name a day after him is to take the very abominations Yahuah listed in Deuteronomy and stamp them onto the middle of the week.
      </p>

      <h2>Two Clocks That Cannot Be Mixed</h2>

      <p>
        Some will ask: <em>"What day in Yahuah's calendar is Wednesday really?"</em> The question itself misunderstands the two systems.
      </p>

      <p>
        Wednesday is a Roman day named after Mercury, then renamed in the Germanic world after the chief Norse god. It belongs to Babylon's clock — the continuous seven-day rotation tied to pagan deities. Yahuah's clock does not have a Wednesday. Yahuah's days are counted from the new moon He hung in the heavens. The new moon is Day 1 of the month — a non-work day, though not a Sabbath. From there the days are numbered, and the Sabbaths fall on Days 8, 15, 22, and 29. When the next new moon appears, the count resets.
      </p>

      <p>
        <strong>There is no Wednesday in this system.</strong> Yahuah's days are counted from the new moon He set in the firmament — not from the name of a wizard who hung himself on a tree to learn runes. The Roman week and Yahuah's reckoning are two different clocks, running on different principles, and they do not translate into each other.
      </p>

      <h2>What to Do With It</h2>

      <p>
        Knowing where the name "Wednesday" came from does not necessarily mean a believer must stop saying it. But knowing the origin matters. The middle day of the Roman week carries the name of a sorcerer-god who patronized everything Yahuah's people are forbidden to touch. Most who say "Wednesday" have no idea — but the name was put there deliberately, by a people who worshiped Woden, and the name has not changed in over a thousand years.
      </p>

      <p>
        <strong>Yahuah's clock and Babylon's clock are not the same clock.</strong> The faithful watch the heavens and let the new moon tell them what day it is. The world watches its phone and lets a wizard-god tell it what day it is. The two answers are as far apart as east is from west.
      </p>

      <div class="pg-pull">
        Wednesday is Woden's day. The runes he hung on a tree to learn are precisely the divination Yahuah called an abomination. The heavens know nothing about him.
      </div>

